\begin_layout Standard
The spring force is the force exerted by a compressed or stretched spring
 upon any object that is attached to it.
 An object that compresses or stretches a spring is always acted upon by
 a force that restores the object to its rest or equilibrium position.
 The spring force is also a result of electromagnetic forces between molecules
 of the spring.
 The spring froce is given by Hooke's law.
 According to Hooke's law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\emph on
the magnitude of the spring force is directly proportional to the amount
 of stretch or compression of the spring and is always directed oppositie
 to the direction of displacement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In symbols if 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 denotes the spring force and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 denotes the extension(or compression) of the spring, then according to
 Hooke's law
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\propto x
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=kx;
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is know as the spring constant.
 Its unit is 
\begin_inset Formula $N/m$
\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 denotes the stiffness of spring.
 Higher 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 value spring require larger force to produce displacement.
\end_layout

