\begin_layout Subsection
Friction force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The force of friction is yet another type of contact force that exists between
 surfaces in contact.
 There are three kinds friction forces that exist between solid surfaces.
 Static frition, sliding friction and rolling or kinetic friction.
 The friction force is always opposite to the direction of motion.
 Static friction tends to oppose the motion of an object kept at rest.
 It is found that the friction force directly proportional to the normal
 reaction.
 In case of static frictoin, the maximum or the limiting value of force
 of friction is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{S}=\mu_{S}N;
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{S}$
\end_inset

 is known as coefficient of static friction.
 Once the object starts moving the friction force decreases and is known
 as sliding friction.
 The sliding friction is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{K}=\mu_{K}N;
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{K}$
\end_inset

 is known as coefficient of kinetic friction.
 In case of a round object rolling such as a wheel, the friction force that
 exists between the surfaces is known as rolling friction.
 The value of rolling friction is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{R}=\mu_{R}N.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In general it is found that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{S}>\mu_{K}>\mu_{R}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Friction force is a non-conservative force.
 Presence of friction causes the mechanical energy to decrease or convert
 into heat energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Viscosity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Viscosity can be considered as a friction force that exists between fluids
 and/or fluids and solids.
 In general viscosity is a force that tends to depend upon the relative
 motioe n speed of the adjacent parts of fluids.
 Such a fluid is known as viscous fluid.
 Viscosity like friction is a non-conservative force.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Uniform circular motion-centripetal force
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often we come across examples of motion in which an object revolves in circular
 path around a point called the center.
 A merry-go-round, a stone tied to a string when revolved, a fan rotating
 around its axis, the earth revolving around sun or the moon revolving around
 earth, an electron revolving around nucleaus are all examples of motion
 known as circular motion.
 Circular motion is only possible if there exists a force that binds the
 object towards the centre; such a force is therefore called the centripetal
 force.
 In uniform circular motion the speed of object remains constant while its
 direction keeps on changing; hence it is an accelerated motion, the correspondi
ng acceleration is known as centripetal acceleration.
 Centripetal force is not a new kind of force but is just a term given in
 reference to uniform circular motion.
 The centripetal force can be any of the forces previously discussed.
 For example in the case of a stone tied to string, the force that keeps
 the stone in its path is the tension force; hence tension is the centripetal
 force in this case.
 In the case of earth revolving around sun, the centripetal force is the
 gravitational force between the sun and the earth.
 In the case of the electron it is the electromagnetic force which binds
 it to the nucleus is the centripetal force.
 
\end_layout

