\begin_layout Standard
If the centripetal force is due to gravity we have the Newton's law of gravitati
on.
 If it is electromagnetic force we have the Coulomb's law.
 But in most cases it may not possible to find an exact formula for centripetal
 force.
 But one can still calculate the value of centripetal force based on the
 properties of the object that revolves.
 Consider a stone of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 tied to a string of length 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and is being revolved with a constant speed of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 The formula for centripetal force is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=\frac{mv^{2}}{r}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In case of the stone as long as the stone keeps revolving the tension force
 is the centripetal force and we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T=\frac{mv^{2}}{r}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If we observe from the frame of reference of the object the object feels
 the force which pushes it away from the center (due to inertia).
 This force is known as centrifugal force.
 The centrifugal force is not a “real” force — the tendency to fly outwards
 is observed because objects that are moving in a straight line tend to
 continue moving in a straight line.
 This is called inertia, and it makes objects resistant to the force that
 makes them move in a curve.
 The value of the centrifugal force is also given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=\frac{mv^{2}}{r}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If an object is properly rotating, both the centrifugal and centripetal
 forces will be equal, so the object will not move towards the center of
 revolution or outwards from it.
 It will maintain a constant distance from the center.
\end_layout

