\begin_layout Subsection
Banking of roads
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a bike or car makes a turn at a road, the friction force prevents the
 bike or car from slipping off the track.
 However if the speed of the vehicle is large the friction force may not
 be sufficient to provide the necessary centripetal force.
 In that case the bike may slip.
 So the maximum safe speed can be obtained easily.
 If the mass of the bike is 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and the coefficient of static friction of the track is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{S}$
\end_inset

 and radius of the turning arc is 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mu_{S}N & = & \frac{mv_{\text{safe}}^{2}}{r}\\
\mu_{S}mg & = & \frac{mv_{\text{safe}}^{2}}{r}\\
v_{\text{safe}} & = & \sqrt{\mu_{S}rg}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

